import wget
for i in range(1,16):
  ### Downloading data from the csv file directly from the hyperlink in the website
  # Walking
  URL_walking = f"https://www.uni-mannheim.de/media/Einrichtungen/dws/Files_Research/Projects/sensor/realworld/s{i}/data/acc_walking_csv.zip"
  response_walking = wget.download(URL_walking, f"acc_walking_{i}.zip")

  # Running
  URL_running = f"https://www.uni-mannheim.de/media/Einrichtungen/dws/Files_Research/Projects/sensor/realworld/s{i}/data/acc_running_csv.zip"
  response_running = wget.download(URL_running, f"acc_running_{i}.zip")
  
  # Climbing Up
  URL_climbingup = f"https://www.uni-mannheim.de/media/Einrichtungen/dws/Files_Research/Projects/sensor/realworld/s{i}/data/acc_climbingup_csv.zip"
  response_climbingup = wget.download(URL_climbingup, f"acc_climbingup_{i}.zip")

  # Climbing Down
  URL_climbingdown = f"https://www.uni-mannheim.de/media/Einrichtungen/dws/Files_Research/Projects/sensor/realworld/s{i}/data/acc_climbingdown_csv.zip"
  response_climbingdown = wget.download(URL_climbingdown, f"acc_climbingdown_{i}.zip")

  ### Unzipping the file
  import zipfile
  # Walking
  with zipfile.ZipFile(f"acc_walking_{i}.zip","r") as zip_ref:
      zip_ref.extractall(f"/content/subject_{i}")

  # Running
  with zipfile.ZipFile(f"acc_running_{i}.zip","r") as zip_ref:
      zip_ref.extractall(f"/content/subject_{i}")

  # Climbing Up
  with zipfile.ZipFile(f"acc_climbingup_{i}.zip","r") as zip_ref:
      zip_ref.extractall(f"/content/subject_{i}")

  # Climbing Down
  with zipfile.ZipFile(f"acc_climbingdown_{i}.zip","r") as zip_ref:
      zip_ref.extractall(f"/content/subject_{i}")

### Reading all datasets as python dataframes
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

for i in range (1,16):
  for activity in ['walking', 'running', 'climbingup', 'climbingdown']:
    for bodypart in ['head', 'chest']:
      dynamic_var_name = 'subject_'+str(i)+'_'+activity+'_'+bodypart
      path = f'/content/subject_{i}/acc_{activity}_{bodypart}.csv'
      ### As there are some paths with files stored in this format
      path2 = f'/content/subject_{i}/acc_{activity}_2_{bodypart}.csv'
      ### As some subjects have multiple zip files within zip files
      path3 = f'/content/subject_{i}/acc_{activity}_1_csv.zip'
      import os
      if os.path.exists(path):
        globals()[dynamic_var_name] = pd.read_csv(path)
      elif os.path.exists(path2):
        globals()[dynamic_var_name] = pd.read_csv(path2)
      elif os.path.exists(path3):
        ### Unzipping and taking the first csv in case a zip inside a zip is found
        with zipfile.ZipFile(f"{path3}","r") as zip_ref:
          zip_ref.extractall(f"/content/subject_{i}")
        globals()[dynamic_var_name] = pd.read_csv(path)

### Collating data
for table in var2:
  q = f"""
         SELECT CASE WHEN '{table}' like '%01%' then 1
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%02%' then 2
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%03%' then 3
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%04%' then 4
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%05%' then 5
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%06%' then 6
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%07%' then 7
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%08%' then 8
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%09%' then 9
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%10%' then 10
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%11%' then 11
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%12%' then 12
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%13%' then 13
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%14%' then 14
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%15%' then 15
                     ELSE -999
                END AS subject,
                CASE WHEN '{table}' like '%walking%' then 'Walking'
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%running%' then 'Running'
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%climbingup%' then 'Climbing Up'
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%climbingdown%' then 'Climbing Down'
                     ELSE 'Check'
                END AS activity,
                CASE WHEN '{table}' like '%chest%' then 'Chest'
                     WHEN '{table}' like '%head%' then 'Head'
                     ELSE 'Check'
                END AS part,
                *

         FROM {table}
         """
  df2 = pysqldf(q)
  df = df.append(df2)

for sub in range(1,16):
  for act in ['Walking', 'Running', 'Climbing Up', 'Climbing Down']:
    for prt in ['Head','Chest']:
      ### For the computations, selecting sample size of 1024 data points (from 1000 to 2024) for each of the time series

      data=df[(df['subject']==sub) & (df['activity']==act) & (df['part']==prt)][1000:2024]

      ### Applying HVG and appending records to the output dataframe
      from ts2vg import HorizontalVG
      g = HorizontalVG()
      g.build(data['attr_x'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'HVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'x', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

      g.build(data['attr_y'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'HVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'y', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

      g.build(data['attr_z'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'HVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'z', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

      ### Applying NVG and appending records to the output dataframe
      from ts2vg import NaturalVG
      g = NaturalVG()
      g.build(data['attr_x'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'NVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'x', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

      g.build(data['attr_y'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'NVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'y', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

      g.build(data['attr_z'])
      ig_g = g.as_igraph()
      output = output.append({'method': 'NVG', 'subject': sub, 'activity': act, 'part': prt, 'accelerometer_axis': 'z', 'avg_degree': np.mean(ig_g.degree()), 'network_diameter': ig_g.diameter(), 'average_path_length': ig_g.average_path_length()}, ignore_index=True)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

count = 1
plt.subplots(figsize=(25, 45))

### NOTE: The first 12 subplots are for walking vs running for all axes, 2 body part positions, and 2 methods. The last 12 subplots are for climbing up vs climbing down

for activity in [['Walking', 'Running'], ['Climbing Up', 'Climbing Down']]:
  for method in ['HVG','NVG']:
    for part in ['Head', 'Chest']:
      for accelerometer_axis in ['x','y','z']:
        data_plot = output[(output['method']==f'{method}') &
                           ((output['activity']==f'{activity[0]}')|(output['activity']==f'{activity[1]}')) &
                           (output['part']==f'{part}') &
                           (output['accelerometer_axis']==f'{accelerometer_axis}')]

        ax = plt.subplot(8,3,count)
        sns.scatterplot(data=data_plot, x='avg_degree', y='network_diameter', hue='activity')
        plt.title(f"Method: {method}, Body Part Position: {part}, Accelerometer Axis: {accelerometer_axis}")
        count = count + 1

### Function for computing permutation entropy and complexity

''' This module has essential functions supporting
fast and effective computation of permutation entropy and
its different variations.'''
import numpy as np


def s_entropy(freq_list):
    ''' This function computes the shannon entropy of a given frequency distribution.
    USAGE: shannon_entropy(freq_list)
    ARGS: freq_list = Numeric vector representing the frequency distribution
    OUTPUT: A numeric value representing shannon's entropy'''
    freq_list = [element for element in freq_list if element != 0]
    sh_entropy = 0.0
    for freq in freq_list:
        sh_entropy += freq * np.log(freq)
    sh_entropy = -sh_entropy
    return(sh_entropy)

def ordinal_patterns(ts, embdim, embdelay):
    ''' This function computes the ordinal patterns of a time series for a given embedding dimension and embedding delay.
    USAGE: ordinal_patterns(ts, embdim, embdelay)
    ARGS: ts = Numeric vector representing the time series, embdim = embedding dimension (3<=embdim<=7 prefered range), embdelay =  embdding delay
    OUPTUT: A numeric vector representing frequencies of ordinal patterns'''
    m, t = embdim, embdelay
    x = ts if isinstance(ts, np.ndarray) else np.array(ts) 

    tmp = np.zeros((x.shape[0], m))
    for i in range(m):
        tmp[:, i] = np.roll(x, i*t)
    partition = tmp[(t*m-1):, :] 
    permutation = np.argsort(partition)
    idx = _hash(permutation)

    counts = np.zeros(np.math.factorial(m))
    for i in range(counts.shape[0]):
        counts[i] = (idx == i).sum()
    return list(counts[counts != 0].astype(int))

def _hash(x):
    m, n = x.shape
    if n == 1:
        return np.zeros(m)
    return np.sum(np.apply_along_axis(lambda y: y < x[:, 0], 0, x), axis=1) * np.math.factorial(n-1) + _hash(x[:, 1:]) 
    

def p_entropy(op):
    ordinal_pat = op
    max_entropy = np.log(len(ordinal_pat))
    p = np.divide(np.array(ordinal_pat), float(sum(ordinal_pat)))
    return(s_entropy(p)/max_entropy)

def complexity(op):
    ''' This function computes the complexity of a time series defined as: Comp_JS = Q_o * JSdivergence * pe
    Q_o = Normalizing constant
    JSdivergence = Jensen-Shannon divergence
    pe = permutation entopry
    ARGS: ordinal pattern'''
    pe = p_entropy(op)
    constant1 = (0.5+((1 - 0.5)/len(op)))* np.log(0.5+((1 - 0.5)/len(op)))
    constant2 = ((1 - 0.5)/len(op))*np.log((1 - 0.5)/len(op))*(len(op) - 1)
    constant3 = 0.5*np.log(len(op))
    Q_o = -1/(constant1+constant2+constant3)

    temp_op_prob = np.divide(op, sum(op))
    temp_op_prob2 = (0.5*temp_op_prob)+(0.5*(1/len(op)))
    JSdivergence = (s_entropy(temp_op_prob2) - 0.5 * s_entropy(temp_op_prob) - 0.5 * np.log(len(op)))
    Comp_JS = Q_o * JSdivergence * pe
    return(Comp_JS)

def weighted_ordinal_patterns(ts, embdim, embdelay):
    m, t = embdim, embdelay
    x = ts if isinstance(ts, np.ndarray) else np.array(ts) 

    tmp = np.zeros((x.shape[0], m))
    for i in range(m):
        tmp[:, i] = np.roll(x, i*t)
    partition = tmp[(t*m-1):, :] 
    xm = np.mean(partition, axis=1)
    weight = np.mean((partition - xm[:, None])**2, axis=1)
    permutation = np.argsort(partition)
    idx = _hash(permutation)
    counts = np.zeros(np.math.factorial(m))
    for i in range(counts.shape[0]):
        counts[i] = sum(weight[i == idx])

    return list(counts[counts != 0])

### Running multiple for loops to dynamically populate the result table for task 2
### NOTE: For each combination, only signal length from 1000:1000+signal_length has been considered

for subject in range(1,16):
  for activity in ['walking', 'running', 'climbingup', 'climbingdown']:
    for part in ['chest', 'head']:
      for accelerometer_axis in ['x','y','z']:
        for embedded_dimension in [3, 4, 5, 6]:
          for embedded_delay in [1, 2, 3]:
            for signal_length in [1024, 2048, 4096]:
              if subject>9:
                exec(f"data = subject_{subject}_{activity}_{part}['attr_{accelerometer_axis}'][1000:1000+signal_length]")
              else:
                exec(f"data = subject_0{subject}_{activity}_{part}['attr_{accelerometer_axis}'][1000:1000+signal_length]")

              op=ordinal_patterns(data, embedded_dimension, embedded_delay)
              output = output.append({'subject': subject, 
                                      'accelerometer_axis': accelerometer_axis, 
                                      'signal_length': signal_length, 
                                      'embedded_dimension': embedded_dimension, 
                                      'embedded_delay': embedded_delay, 
                                      'part': part, 
                                      'activity': activity,
                                      'permutation_entropy': p_entropy(op), 
                                      'complexity': complexity(op)}, ignore_index=True)

        ax = plt.subplot(16,3,count)
        sns.scatterplot(data=data_plot, x='permutation_entropy', y='complexity', hue='activity')
        plt.title(f"Embedded Dimension: {embedded_dimension}, Body Position: {part}, Accelerometer Axis: {accelerometer_axis}")
        count = count + 1
